DynamoDB operations, and D-A-X.

There are four shapes of read in DynamoDB, with very different cost profiles. Get-item fetches a single item by its primary key; it's the cheapest and fastest read. Query fetches items within one partition-key value, optionally filtered by a sort-key range; it's efficient because it only reads the relevant partition, and it's the workhorse of DynamoDB access patterns. Scan reads every item in the table and then filters, charging capacity for the entire table regardless of how many items match; it's almost always wrong in production, and if you find yourself reaching for Scan, the access pattern probably wants a G-S-I instead. And batch-get-item and batch-write-item do up to a hundred gets or twenty-five writes in one call, saving round-trips but not capacity. One trap: filter expressions apply after the read, so items that get filtered out still cost capacity; they trim the response payload, not the bill.

D-A-X, the DynamoDB Accelerator, is an in-memory cache purpose-built for DynamoDB. It delivers microsecond reads on cache hits, versus single-digit milliseconds for DynamoDB itself, and it's drop-in compatible with the DynamoDB S-D-K, so you swap the client and existing code works unchanged. It's write-through: writes go to DynamoDB first, then update the D-A-X cache on success. It has two separate caches with independent T-T-Ls, five minutes for the item cache and one minute for the query cache. And it runs V-P-C-only and multi-A-Z, as a cluster of nodes with private I-Ps. Reach for D-A-X when a DynamoDB workload is read-heavy on hot items and needs microsecond latency; it's not for write-heavy workloads, and it serves eventually-consistent reads, so not for strong-consistency needs.
